  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Washington DC who grew up in a modest family with parents who only had vocational diplomas, I’ve seen firsthand how education and opportunity can change lives. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the quiet barriers that keep women from pursuing careers in fields like engineering or physics. My own experience as a mother of two and a woman who studied beyond my initial upper secondary education taught me that confidence and support matter more than innate ability. When I was younger, I remember my parents encouraging me to learn practical skills, but they never pushed me into the sciences. That’s a missed opportunity for many women today. The gap exists because society often steers girls away from STEM early on, assuming they’re less interested or capable. But addressing this isn’t about changing girls’ minds—it’s about changing the system. I’ve seen it in my community: girls who excel in math but are discouraged from pursuing engineering because they’re told it’s “too tough.” We need to create mentorship programs that start early, in schools, where girls can see themselves in scientific roles. Also, workplaces must be more inclusive—no more gendered language in job descriptions or promotions. My husband and I, as a married couple who’ve lived in DC for decades, have noticed how much more women feel isolated in male-dominated fields. This gap is solvable, but it requires patience and a commitment to equality from all of us. It’s not just about fixing the gap—it’s about building a future where every girl has the chance to dream big.",
